    {
        "content": "<p>Hello all! This is the thread of discussion for the talk of Jules Hedges, \"Non-compositionality in categorical systems theory\".<br>\nDate and time: Monday July 6, 12:10 UTC.<br>\nZoom meeting: <a href=\"https://mit.zoom.us/j/7055345747\">https://mit.zoom.us/j/7055345747</a><br>\nYouTube live stream: <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1A76CO3K28U&amp;list=PLCOXjXDLt3pZDHGYOIqtg1m1lLOURjl1Q\">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1A76CO3K28U&amp;list=PLCOXjXDLt3pZDHGYOIqtg1m1lLOURjl1Q</a></p>\n<div class=\"youtube-video message_inline_image\"><a data-id=\"1A76CO3K28U\" href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1A76CO3K28U&amp;list=PLCOXjXDLt3pZDHGYOIqtg1m1lLOURjl1Q\"><img src=\"https://i.ytimg.com/vi/1A76CO3K28U/default.jpg\"></a></div>",
        "id": 202645025,
        "sender_full_name": "Paolo Perrone",
        "timestamp": 1593657569
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>My slides: <a href=\"https://obsoletewallstreet.files.wordpress.com/2020/07/categorical_systems_theory.pdf\">https://obsoletewallstreet.files.wordpress.com/2020/07/categorical_systems_theory.pdf</a></p>",
        "id": 202974169,
        "sender_full_name": "Jules Hedges",
        "timestamp": 1594031904
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>We start in 2 minutes!</p>",
        "id": 202980338,
        "sender_full_name": "Paolo Perrone",
        "timestamp": 1594037303
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I'm wondering what guarantees that the set of comorphisms is a set rather than a proper class (unless your category is small)? Is some quotioning along some equivalence relation on contexts doing the work in the background?</p>",
        "id": 202982343,
        "sender_full_name": "Martti Karvonen",
        "timestamp": 1594038783
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Really enjoyed your talk, Jules! I'm wondering about a possible example. In <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/1704.02051\">Compositional Framework for Reaction Networks</a> they define a black-boxing functor out of the category of continuous open dynamical systems. This black-box is trying to capture the behavior of \"steady states.\" Unfortunately, pure steady states is only lax functorial and there may be emergent steady states. As a solution to making the black-box functorial, the behavior they choose is  instead \"steady states and a flow on the boundary which keeps the state steady.\" I wonder if this \"flow on the boundary\" is an example of a context?</p>",
        "id": 203013325,
        "sender_full_name": "Sophie Libkind",
        "timestamp": 1594054067
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Oo, nice idea, I'll definitely look into that</p>",
        "id": 203013599,
        "sender_full_name": "Jules Hedges",
        "timestamp": 1594054222
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I'm on the hunt for a collection of nice examples, until then I have no real reason to write a paper about this...</p>",
        "id": 203013637,
        "sender_full_name": "Jules Hedges",
        "timestamp": 1594054254
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I've actually been thinking about generalizing this exact black boxing functor but as a transformation between operad algebras</p>",
        "id": 203013667,
        "sender_full_name": "Sophie Libkind",
        "timestamp": 1594054276
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Does the context formalism generalize to operad algebras?</p>",
        "id": 203013680,
        "sender_full_name": "Sophie Libkind",
        "timestamp": 1594054290
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I think it should. Working out the conditions it should satisfy might take some work</p>",
        "id": 203013840,
        "sender_full_name": "Jules Hedges",
        "timestamp": 1594054383
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Hey guys! I have also been precisely thinking about this problem lately (and <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"275901\">@Jules Hedges</span> I was meaning to e-mail you and <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"276165\">@Eigil Rischel</span> about this because I think my systems are related to the discussion I saw between you on Twitter). This 'flow on the boundary' thing is (I think) very closely related to something I briefly e-mailed <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"276589\">@Sophie Libkind</span>  about, with respect to Lagrangian dynamics; and in this case, the composition of my systems seems very clearly operadic (roughly, the physical intuition is like \"particles within particles\"). I'll write up some notes on my system and send them round :-)</p>",
        "id": 203014693,
        "sender_full_name": "Toby Smithe",
        "timestamp": 1594054837
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I guess you want a set of contexts for every type (i.e color) in your operad, which is in some sense \"reverse functorial\" in the algebra describing your systems - i.e if you have an operad operation <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>o</mi><mo>:</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>a</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>b</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>→</mo><mi>c</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">o: (a,b) \\to c</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">o</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">a</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.16666666666666666em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">b</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">c</span></span></span></span>, a context of type <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>c</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">c</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">c</span></span></span></span> and a system of type <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>a</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">a</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">a</span></span></span></span>, you obtain a context of type <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>b</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">b</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.69444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">b</span></span></span></span></p>",
        "id": 203014975,
        "sender_full_name": "Eigil Rischel",
        "timestamp": 1594054989
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>We can take a coalgebra of our operad, by which I mean an algbra in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>S</mi><mi>e</mi><msup><mi>t</mi><mrow><mi>o</mi><mi>p</mi></mrow></msup><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mo>×</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">(Set^{op},\\times)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">S</span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">e</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">t</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.664392em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathdefault mtight\">o</span><span class=\"mord mathdefault mtight\">p</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.16666666666666666em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">×</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>. This means there's a map from <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>C</mi><mi>t</mi><mi>x</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>c</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>→</mo><mi>C</mi><mi>t</mi><mi>x</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>a</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>b</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Ctx(c) \\to Ctx(a,b)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">t</span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">x</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">c</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">t</span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">x</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">a</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.16666666666666666em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">b</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> in the situation above. Then maybe pasting a system into a context is some sort of action of the algebra of systems on this gadget?</p>",
        "id": 203016064,
        "sender_full_name": "Eigil Rischel",
        "timestamp": 1594055582
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>What does it mean to have a coalgebra of an operad? And this coalgebra would be the contexts <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>C</mi><mi>t</mi><mi>x</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Ctx</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">t</span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">x</span></span></span></span>?</p>",
        "id": 203018001,
        "sender_full_name": "Sophie Libkind",
        "timestamp": 1594056639
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yeah, by that I meant an algebra in an opposite category of sets (but still with cartesian product as monoidal structure). But now that you mention it, this doesn't seem quite right - given an operation <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>o</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>a</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>b</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>→</mo><mi>c</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">o(a,b) \\to c</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">o</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">a</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.16666666666666666em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">b</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">c</span></span></span></span>, and a context of type <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>c</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">c</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">c</span></span></span></span>, I don't expect to find two contexts of type <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>a</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">a</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">a</span></span></span></span> and type <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>b</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">b</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.69444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">b</span></span></span></span>.. so something's off here.</p>",
        "id": 203018247,
        "sender_full_name": "Eigil Rischel",
        "timestamp": 1594056807
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Here's the video!<br>\n<a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JxvmjOZbv7U&amp;list=PLCOXjXDLt3pYot9VNdLlZqGajHyZUywdI\">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JxvmjOZbv7U&amp;list=PLCOXjXDLt3pYot9VNdLlZqGajHyZUywdI</a></p>\n<div class=\"youtube-video message_inline_image\"><a data-id=\"JxvmjOZbv7U\" href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JxvmjOZbv7U&amp;list=PLCOXjXDLt3pYot9VNdLlZqGajHyZUywdI\"><img src=\"https://i.ytimg.com/vi/JxvmjOZbv7U/default.jpg\"></a></div>",
